# Plot one variable four different ways:
eclipse_time = lunar['Penumbral Eclipse Duration (m)']

f, ((ax1, ax2), (ax3, ax4)) = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize = (18, 11))

sns.distplot(a = eclipse_time, ax = ax1)
ax1.set(xlabel = "Penumbral Eclipse Duration (Minutes)", ylabel = "Number of Eclipses")


sns.kdeplot(data = eclipse_time, ax = ax2)
ax2.set(xlabel = "Penumbral Eclipse Duration (Minutes)", ylabel = "Number of Eclipses")

sns.lvplot(data = eclipse_time, orient = 'h', ax = ax3)
ax3.set(xlabel = "Penumbral Eclipse Duration (Minutes)", ylabel = "Number of Eclipses")

sns.boxplot(data = eclipse_time, orient = 'h', ax = ax4)
ax4.set(xlabel = "Penumbral Eclipse Duration (Minutes)", ylabel = "Number of Eclipses")

plt.show()

# Challenge questions (helpful two look at two continuous variables):
# This looks at the relationship between a person's popularity index and the number of languages their profiles
# have been translated into.  You can see that it is a bivariate relationship, with a positive correlation and albeit
# not the strongest positive correlation, it is present. Regarding the probability distribution, you can see that a
# higher popularity index will usually lead to a profile that is translated into more languages.  My guess is that you 
# would see a positive stronger correlation if we had a more diverse language set (i.e. if English, Spanish, French,
# Chinese, etc. weren't spoken by as many people and you had smaller subsets of diversely speaking peoples.)

sns.jointplot(x = "historical_popularity_index", y = "article_languages", 
              data = popularity, kind = 'reg', )
plt.show()
